Cell.Data: A thing that discourages or is intended to discourage someone from doing something.
The security guard acts as a deterrent for tailgaters and trespassers.
The newspaper was duped into publishing an untrue story.
Tending to be different or develop in different directions.
The Nile River separates into two divergent rivers near Ethiopia.
Proceeding in a gradual, subtle way, but with harmful effects.
Cancer is a very insidious disease that often grows without notice.
Having or showing a tendency to be easily angered.
My dad is irascible because he is in pain.
Unwilling to spend money or use resources; stingy or frugal.
Curtis needs to be more parsimonious and stop buying so many books.
Lasting for a very short time.
Drugs give people ephemeral happiness and are totally worth it!!
Begin to grow or increase rapidly; flourish.
The price for a barrel of bourbon has burgeoned from $15 to over $250.
Intended or likely to placate or pacify.
The client was conciliatory toward the auditors by providing chairs and tables to work on.
Exaggerate or feign illness in order to escape duty or work.
The student was sick so often that others suspected him of malingering.
Match or surpass, typically by imitation.
My sister emulates me during dinner when I tell her to eat her food.
Starting a new career in your thirties can seem like a daunting challenge.
Famous or well known, typically for some bad quality or deed.
Mandy was notorious for putting out on the first date.
1) Not allowing fluid to pass through. 2) Unable to be affected by.
This raincoat is impervious to water.
(of a person or their tendencies) not able to be corrected, improved, or reformed.
Julie's behavior was incorrigible so she was grounded for a year.
Avoiding the company of other people; solitary.
Studying for the GMAT/GRE made her into a recluse.
Having a ready insight into and understanding of things.
Einstein was perspicacious and learned very quickly.
A state of physical or mental weariness; lack of energy.
Treating serious issues with deliberately inappropriate humor; flippant.
His facetious remarks are often taken too seriously.
A whole formed by combining several (typically separate) elements.
Without a clearly defined shape or form.
Reach an authoritative judgment or settlement.
Severe or strict in manner, attitude, or appearance.
A person who gives money or other help to a person or cause.
A person or thing that precipitates an event.
A concluding event, remark, or section.
A confusing and difficult problem or question.
A temporary departure from the main subject in speech or writing.
A lack of compatibility or similarity between two or more facts.
Essentially different in kind; not allowing comparison.
Order or allow to leave; send away.
An indirect expression referring to something rude, embarrassing, or unpleasant.
Attempting to avoid notice or attention; secretive.
The pursuit of pleasure; sensual self-indulgence.
A person who attacks cherished beliefs or institutions.
Not resulting from or achieved through deliberate planning.
Lacking the ability or strength to move.
Hard to control or deal with.
Having or showing a sharp or critical quality; biting.
Surprise or confuse (someone) so much that they are unsure how to react.
Having an unemotional and stolidly calm disposition.
Dealing with things sensibly, realistically, and practically rather than theoretically.
Attempting to impress through exaggerated importance, talent, or culture.
Remarkably or impressively great in extend, size, or degree.
An inclination or natural tendency to behave in a particular way.
A thing that protrudes from something else.
In a state or period of inactivity or dormancy.
Address (someone) in such a way as to express disapproval or disappointment.
Not revealing ones thoughts or feelings readily.
A threatened penalty for disobeying a law or rule.
Superficially plausible, but actually wrong. Misleading.
Reserved or uncommunicative in speech; saying little.
Alternate or waver between different opinions or actions.
Make (someone) feel annoyed, frustrated, or worried, especially with trivial matters.
